Introduction¶

Agriculture is central to how our societies function. The development of agriculture allowed humans to devote time to something other than gathering and hunting food. Farms provide food for our communities. The agricultural industry is also responsible for large amounts of greenhouse gas emissions. Fertilizer production, transportation of food, and livestock management are energy-intensive processes.

For the following investigation, I selected three datasets from Gapminder:

  1. agricultural land as a percentage of total land area,
  2. annual CO$_2$ emissions in metric tonnes of CO$_2$ per person , and
  3. income per person (GDP/capita).

These factors are influenced by a myriad of global and local factors, so correlation might be low. Despite this, I was curious to determine how the amount of agricultural land has changed over time and if those changes correlate with changes in CO$_2$ emissions. If those do not, is GDP a better indicator of CO2 emissions in the time frame of interest?

Agricultural land¶

The code above (when not suppressed with a semicolon) shows that the data are all floats. Additionally, from 1961-1990 30 countries are missing data, between 1992 and 2005 2-8 countries are missing data. There is no missing data from 2005-present. After transposing to look at data by country, I saw that countries either had 0 missing values or ~30 missing values. This suggests that the missing data aren't randomly distributed; some countries only have more recent data.

Thoughts¶

In the newer data, there are more countries with more land set aside for agriculture. From these histograms, it isn't possible to discern whether countries are adding more land for agriculture or whether the countries added after 1961 (30 missing countries) tend to use more of their land for agriculture. Despite this, the data do skew right in 1961 and seem somewhat more evenly distributed in 1993 (4 missing countries) and 2016 (0 missing countries). 1993, with only 4 missing data points, shows a roughly even distribution.

I'd like to be able to focus in a little more on countries who have significantly changed the amount of land they are using for agriculture.

Research question 2: Is the change in agricultural land reflected in CO$_2$ emissions for a country?¶

Because agriculture can be responsible for a larger percentage of greenhouse gas emissions, I'm curious to see if changes in agricultural land area are reflected in CO$_2$ emissions. To answer this question, I first filtered the data so that I was only using countries whose agricultural land area had changed by at least 25%. This made these large datasets a little easier to visually compare. Then, I plotted change in agricultural land area and change in CO$_2$ emissions for the countries that added and lost land for agriculture.

Observations¶

Land increase¶

Saudi Arabia has significantly increased the amount of land devoted to agriculture and also emitted far more CO$_2$ in 2016 than in 1961. I believe they have set up some large-scale irrigation efforts, so the increase in arable land makes sense. The CO$_2$ could be related to agriculture or to other changes. Costa Rica shows a huge spike in land area the 1980s, then a more recent drop in agricultural land area. This may correlate with a spike in its CO$_2$ emissions, but it is difficult to tell because the Saudi Arabia data swamps the scale of the graph. Otherwise, the overall trend is gradually increasing amounts of land used for agriculture and CO$_2$ emissions.

Land decrease¶

These countries show a gradual decrease in available land area. All of these countries, except Italy, are islands (and tourist destinations).

Observations¶

There are some interesting trends here:

  1. countries with high CO2 emissions tend to not have much of their land used for agriculture
  2. countries with low CO$_2$ emissions are more likely to devote more of their land to agriculture
  3. Countries that have added agricultural land are more likely to be low CO$_2$ emitters
  4. Countries that emit more CO$_2$ have changed the amount of CO$_2$ they emit to a much greater degree than the other countries plotted here
  5. Strongly agricultural countries are not the greatest emitters
  6. Many countries whose agricultural land area decreases still see a general increase in CO$_2$ emissions.

When taken together, these data do not show a strong correlation between a country's CO$_2$ emissions and agricultural land. Rather, they both change incrementally over time.

Research question 3: Is GDP a better indicator for CO$_2$ emissions?¶

The agricultural data do not show the correlation I expected. That's great. I learned something new. However, if agricultural land area doesn't correlate with increasing CO$_2$ emissions, I'm curious to find something that does. Below, I've imported another data set, GDP per capita, to see if there is a correlation between this and the CO$_2$ emissions. I also plot the GDP per capita and agricultural land data together to see if there are relationships there that may help me better understand the factors at play in this investigation.

Research Question 4: A United States Case Study¶

Because these data sets capture so many countries, I'd also like to look specifically at the United States to see what is happening at the single country level. This removes a lot of the potential for variability that exists between different geographic locations, cultures, economies, etc.

#plot the US data
fig5 = plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
ax5 = fig5.add_subplot(111)

y1='Annual CO2 emissions per person in tonnes CO2'
y2='Annual GDP per person (GDP/capita)'

ax5.scatter(unitedstates['ag_land'],unitedstates['co2'], label = c, marker = 'o', color='maroon', alpha = .6)
ax5.set_ylabel(y1, color='maroon')

ax5b = ax5.twinx()
ax5b.scatter(unitedstates['ag_land'],unitedstates['gdp'], label = c, marker = 'o', color = 'teal', alpha = .6)
ax5b.set_ylabel(y2, color='teal')

for tl in ax5.get_yticklabels():
    tl.set_color('maroon')

for tl in ax5b.get_yticklabels():
    tl.set_color('teal')

ax5.set_xlabel('Proportion of a country\'s land used for agriculture')
plt.title('CO2 emissions and GDP per capita vs. proportion of land as agriculture \n for the United States from 1961-2016')

plt.show()

Observations¶

There is something of a negative correlation here. When the proportion of land used for agriculture is high (close to 50%), the GDP is lower and our CO$_2$ emissions are lower. As the land used for agriculture decreases, there is an increase in GDP and carbon emissions. This is the opposite of what I thought I might find, and likely reflects the changing economy and social changes in the US more than the influence of agriculture on either of these, but there's ultimately no way to say using just this data.

Conclusions¶

Question 1: How has the proportion of land used for agriculture over time?¶

It appears that there are more countries now that have more land used for agriculture. However, this could easily reflect a sampling bias as the data from 1961 is missing ~30 countries.

Question 2: Is the change in agricultural land reflected in CO$_2$ emissions for a country?¶

While there are some general trends showing that countries with high emissions are more likely to have less agriculture and countries with more agriculture are somewhat more likely to have lower emissions (the opposite of what I expected). One country that was a noteable exception to this is Saudi Arabia. Saudi Arabia has significantly increased the amount of land used for agriculture and their CO2 emissions in the last 56 years.

Question 3: Is GDP a better indicator for CO$_2$ emissions?¶

Yes. Generally speaking, countries with higher GDP have higher CO$_2$ emissions. Countries with higher GDP also tend to use less of their land for agriculture.

Question 4: A United States case study.¶

The United States has lost agricultural land over the years (the time component of this is not visible from the plot, but was observed in the raw data). It has also increased its GDP and its CO$_2$ emissions. It shows a trend opposite of what I expected.

Final Thoughts¶

I'll admit, I thought there would be somewhat more correlation between these, but these factors are all so large and influenced by so many factors, it is not surprising that it is difficult to see large-scale correlations. It is worth noting that my perceptions going in to this investigation were driven by industrial-style agriculture. This is not reflected in the data. They show only agricultural land percentage. Thus, countries with many small-scale locally-focused farms would have very high agricultural areas, but are likely to be much lower CO$_2$ emitters. When focusing on a single country (the US), there is some more significant correlation (still opposite of my hypothesis), but very little is present on a larger scale.
